					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">The power supply of an NES consists of a brick, a low-voltage cable, and a voltage regulator inside the Control Deck. Nothing after the regulator sees the mains frequencies. And strictly, &quot;NTSC&quot; and &quot;PAL&quot; are misnomers, as the NES sold in Brazil uses NTSC timing (because of 60 Hz mains frequency) but internally converts the NTSC signal to PAL/M. The French NES uses PAL timing but internally converts PAL to RGB on a SCART port because France used SECAM instead of PAL.</div><br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">The regulator converts the varying voltage coming out of the power brick to a more or less constant 5.0 V DC. Little to none of the mains frequency remains, and the PPU generates the 60.1 or 50 Hz time base from a crystal oscillator in the Control Deck. NTSC and PAL decks have different crystals and different PPUs.</div><br />Okay, so if they regulator can convert any kind of mains voltage to the correct 5.0 V, then why did they bother having both 60 Hz and 50 Hz versions? Or, why doesn't the frame rate match the mains frequency in Brazil? Or, maybe I'm getting things mixed up. NTSC and PAL refer to ways of encoding colors in a frame, not the frequency of the frames, right?</div>

